'''Energy in Gabon''' is an [[industry]] with plenty of potential.

==Oil==
[[Gabon]], a former OPEC member (1975–1994) that rejoined in 2016, is the sixth-largest<ref>Gabon Country field, accessed online on 20/05/2014 on http://www.eia.gov/countries/cab.cfm?fips=GB</ref> [[oil]] producer in sub-Saharan Africa, and has the region's fifth-largest oil reserves.<ref>Gabon Country File, accessed online on 30/05/2014 on http://www.eia.gov/countries/cab.cfm?fips=GB</ref> Oil prospecting began in 1931. Deposits were found on the coast or off shore in the vicinity of [[Libreville]], northwestern Gabon and [[Port-Gentil]], along the coast and in the southwestern part of the country. Larger deposits were found in the south. Oil from the northwest is channeled by pipeline to Cape Lopez, where there are loading facilities for export. 
Additional deposits were found on [[Mandji Island]] in 1962. The Rabi Kounga oil field, operated by Shell Gabon, is Gabon's largest oil field. In 1997, it produced a peak of {{convert|217000|oilbbl/d}}. As of November 2004, it was producing {{convert|55000|oilbbl/d}}.

The first national oil company was the [[Société Nationale Petrolière Gabonaise]] but it was disbanded in 1987.  The government of Gabon controls all petroleum and mineral rights within the state. In 2011 a presidential decree created the Gabon Oil Company (GOC).<ref name="gabonoil.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.gabonoil.com/index.php/en/|title=Web Page Under Construction|author=|date=|website=www.gabonoil.com}}</ref> This new entity works in partnership with international companies operating in Gabon and operates two fields: Obangue and Remboue.<ref name="gabonoil.com"/>

==Petroleum==
Although Gabon's proven [[petroleum]] reserves rose from {{convert|1300|Moilbbl}} in 1996 to {{convert|2500|Moilbbl}} in 2004, the government is concerned about long-term depletion of resources. Total production of crude oil fell from a peak of {{convert|371000|oilbbl/d}} day to an estimated {{convert|289700|oilbbl/d}} in 2003. Gabon's production goes primarily to [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], [[France]], the [[United States]], and, more recently, [[Taiwan]]. Net oil exports in 2003 are estimated at 289,680 barrels per day.

As of January 2004, reserves of natural gas reserves estimated at {{convert|1.2|Tcuft}}, by the [[Oil & Gas Journal]]. Production and consumption of natural gas in 2002 were estimated at {{convert|3|Gcuft}}, each. Gross output stood at {{convert|81.22|Gcuft}} in 2002, of which {{convert|55.09|Gcuft}} was flared or vented off, and {{convert|19.42|Gcuft}} was reinjected.

==Hydropower==
{{see also|Grand Poubara Dam}}
In 2002 there were hydroelectric stations at the [[Kinguélé]] and [[Tchimbélé]] dams on the [[Mbei River]] and at the [[Petite Poubara Dam]], near [[Makokou]] on the [[Ogooué]]. Production and distribution of electricity are maintained by the [[Energy and Water Company of Gabon]] (SEEG), which was formed in 1963 and incorporates a number of smaller private and quasi-public entities. In 2002, electric power output totalled an estimated 1.16&nbsp;TWh, with capacity estimated as of January 2002 at 406&nbsp;MW. Consumption of [[electricity]] was 1.275&nbsp;TWh in 2002. [[Natural gas]] is the principal fuel for the thermal plants. Hydropower accounts for 11% of Gabon's electric power consumption in 2013.

