'''Ragnar Frislid''' (29 June 1926 – 14 June 2009) was a Norwegian writer, photographer and environmentalist.
He was born in [[Oslo]]. He was a journalist in ''[[Dagbladet]]'' from 1950 to 1959.<ref name=ntb>{{cite news|title=Ragnar Frislid 75 år 29. juni|agency=Norwegian News Agency|language=Norwegian}}</ref> From 1965 to 1986 he edited ''Norsk Natur'', the magazine released by [[Norwegian Society for the Conservation of Nature]].<ref name=obit>{{cite journal|last=Ådnem|first=Arild |author2=[[Lars Haltbrekken|Haltbrekken, Lars]] |author3=Flatberg, Per |title=Minneord: Ragnar Frislid|journal=Natur & Miljø|publisher=Norwegian Society for the Conservation of Nature|issue=4/2009|pages=35|language=Norwegian}}</ref> He also edited the magazines ''Jakt-Fiske-Friluftsliv'' and ''Fjell og Vidde'' as well as the yearbook of the [[Norwegian Trekking Association]]. He wrote about 30 books, and translated other books.<ref name=ntb/> His 1964 release ''Naturvern'' has been called the first Norwegian book about the conservation of nature.
In 1969 he wrote ''Norske dyr'' ('Animals of Norway') together with [[Arne Semb-Johansson]].<ref name=obit/> His translation ''Verdens dyr'' ('Animals of the World'), from English to Norwegian in 1984, became an issue of dispute in 1992, when the publishing house [[J.W. Cappelens Forlag]] and [[De norske Bokklubbene]] arranged for the making of a second edition. Frislid demanded a new fee of {{NOK|159,579}} in addition to the one-off fee of NOK 319,158 received in 1984.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cappelen-tap i Høyesterett|first=Bjørgulv|last=Braanen|authorlink=Bjørgulv Braanen|date=15 September 1999|work=Dagens Næringsliv|page=45|language=Norwegian}}</ref> The publishing house won the trials in the [[district court (Norway)|district court]] as well as the [[court of appeal (Norway)|court of appeal]], but after years of legal battle, Frislid won in the [[Supreme Court of Norway]] in 1999.<ref>{{cite news|title=Cappelen må betale tilleggshonorar for bokklubbutgivelse|first=Lars Ditlev|last=Hansen|date=15 September 1999|work=Aftenposten|page=16|language=Norwegian}}</ref>
Frislid also contributed to encyclopedias<ref name=obit/> and radio. As a [[nature photography|nature photographer]] he was a part of the Norwegian photo agency [[Samfoto]] and an honorary member of the organization [[Norwegian Nature Photographers]].<ref name=ntb/> He died in June 2009.<ref name=obit/>
